-- Anhui Conch, China Liansu, Standard Chartered: Hong Kong Equities Preview
-- Hanny Wan
-- 2010-06-23T01:26:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-23/anhui-conch-china-liansu-standard-chartered-hong-kong-equities-preview.html

          
          
             The  following  companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close unless
otherwise noted.  
 The  Hang Seng Index  slid 0.5 percent to 20,819.08. The Hang
Seng China Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, dropped 0.6 percent to 12,061.34.  
 Anhui Conch Cement Co.  (914 HK): BNP Paribas cut its rating
on the stock to “hold” from “buy.” Anhui Conch, China’s
biggest cement producer, dropped 3 percent to HK$25.65.  
 China Liansu Group Holdings Ltd.  (2128 HK): The producer of
plumbing supplies sold 750 million shares at HK$2.60 each,
raising net proceeds of HK$1.82 billion ($234 million),
according to a statement. Trading starts today.  
 Henderson Land Development Co.  (12 HK): Hong Kong’s Lands
Department wrote to Henderson Land for the seventh time as part
of its investigation into apartment sales at 39 Conduit Road,
the Standard newspaper reported. The home builder was asked to
provide additional transaction details, specifically how it
calculated the interest penalty for late payments, the newspaper
quoted an unidentified Henderson Land spokeswoman as saying. The
shares advanced 0.1 percent to HK$47.80.  
      Hong Kong Exchanges & Clearing Ltd.  (388 HK): The operator
of Asia’s third-largest stock market said it has held talks with
Brazil’s bourse over potential listings. The stock fell 0.8
percent to HK$126.40.  
      PCCW Ltd.  (8 HK): Morgan Stanley raised its rating on the
stock to “overweight” from “equal-weight” because of the
company’s free cash flow, dividend yields and its cost-saving
initiatives.  
 The brokerage recommended investors to switch to PCCW from
 Hutchison Telecommunications Hong Kong Holdings Ltd.  (215 HK),
which they downgraded to “equal-weight” from “overweight.”  
 PCCW, a Hong Kong phone carrier, dropped 0.5 percent to
HK$2.21. Hutchison Telecom, a provider of mobile and fixed-line
phone services, rose 3 percent to HK$1.73.  
 Standard Chartered Plc  (2888 HK): The U.K. bank that earns
three-quarters of its profit in Asia had its financial strength
outlook changed to “stable” from “negative” by Standard &
Poor’s, which cited the likelihood of resilient 2010 earnings.
The stock dropped 0.9 percent to HK$204.60.  
